title:
Voltage laws in nanodomains revealed by asymptotics and simulations of
  electro-diffusion equations

sections.text:
#### Abstract

Characterizing the local voltage distribution within nanophysiological domains, driven by ionic currents through membrane channels, is crucial for studying cellular activity in modern biophysics, yet it presents significant experimental and theoretical challenges. Theoretically, the complexity arises from the difficulty of solving electro-diffusion equations in three-dimensional domains. Currently, there are no methods available for obtaining asymptotic computations or approximated solutions of nonlinear equations, and numerically, it is challenging to explore solutions across both small and large spatial scales. In this work, we develop a method to solve the Poisson-Nernst-Planck equations with ionic currents entering and exiting through two narrow, circular window channels located on the boundary. The inflow through the first window is composed of a single cation, while the outflow maintains a constant ionic density satisfying local electro-neutrality conditions. Employing regular expansions and Green's function representations, we derive the ionic profiles and voltage drops in both small and large charge regimes. We explore how local surface curvature and window channels size influence voltage dynamics and validate our theoretical predictions through numerical simulations, assessing the accuracy of our asymptotic computations. These novel relationships between current, voltage, concentrations and geometry can enhance the characterization of physiological behaviors of nanodomains.

## 1 Introduction

Studying voltage in nanodomains has been a continuous effort, leading to the modeling and refinement of transistors to microchips in the field of electronic [1], but has also been key to better characterize the role of subcellular domains in cell biology [2]. Indeed, the voltage in such small domains controls many fundamental physiological and metabolic processes, such as the opening and closing of ionic protein channels $[3,4]$, cellular homeostasis [5] or ATP production in mitochondria [6, 7, 8]. However at such nanometer scale, intracellular voltage measurement remains difficult, despite recent experimental advances using nanopipettes $[9,10,11]$ or genetically encoded voltage indicators $[12,13,14]$.
Classical approaches to model neuronal excitability and voltage propagation rely on a Hodgkin-Huxley formalism [15] and the cable or telegraphic equations [16], which treat the plasma membrane as a capacitor with ionic channels as electrical conductors and assume spatially homogeneous ionic concentrations. However these theories do not account for the complex geometry of neuronal nano-structures, such as synapses and dendritic spines, where channel fluxes can lead to ionic concentration gradients and localized spatial perturbations [17, 18]. These changes are small and negligible when the volume is large. But for

nanodomains with volumes of the order of femtoliters $\left(\mu \mathrm{m}^{3}\right)$, we can calculate that in a volume of one $\mu \mathrm{m}^{3}$, an inward current of 1 pA corresponds to an ionic influx of around $10 \mu \mathrm{M}$ per millisecond. Thus, currents of the order of tens or hundreds of pA can significantly alter ionic concentrations within milliseconds.
To address how subcellular geometry and concentration changes contribute to voltage dynamics at such a small scale, alternative modeling approaches have been developed. One example is electro-diffusion theory describing the motion of charged particles within electrolytes [19, 20]. Mathematically it is formulated with the Poisson coupled to Fokker-Planck equations, called Poisson-Nernst-Planck equations: the voltage is computed from the local charge interactions using Poisson, while spatio-temporal dynamics of ionic densities follow Fokker-Planck (drift-diffusion) equations with the electric field driving the drift. These equations have been widely studied in one-dimensional space, with ionic concentrations following Boltzmann distribution allowing a model reduction to a single nonlinear Poisson's equation. This is known as Poisson-Boltzmann theory describing voltage distribution and local charge imbalances near planar membranes [21, 22, 23]. However this geometry and steady-state simplification cannot be used to model ionic fluxes originating from channels and pumps in complex three-dimensional subcellular nanodomains, which is the topic of the current study.
Previous works either focused on the single-charge non-electroneutral case [24, 25, 26, 27] or two-monovalent charges [28, 29, 30], and highlighted for instance how highly curved membrane protrusions, such as a funnelshaped cusp, or how the membrane organization of channels, can modulate voltage dynamics. However realistic nanophysiological domains often involve a more complex interplay of multiple ionic species with varying valences. For instance voltage nanodomains can result of the coactivation of calcium and potassium channels [31] $\left(\mathrm{Ca}_{v}-\mathrm{K}_{v}\right)$, with calcium influx forcing the exit of potassium by creating a voltage nanodomain. The set of valences involved here are $\{+2,+1,-1\}$, the negative valence referring to chloride ions. Our aim here is to study how $n$ ionic species of valence $z_{i}$ with $i=1, \ldots, n$ interact and generate voltage nanodomains between entry and exit channels.
The manuscript is organized as follows. We first provide a brief summary of the main result expressed as current-voltage formulas (Section §2). We formulate the Poisson-Nernst-Planck electro-diffusion model in Section §3. We employ a regular asymptotic expansion to derive ionic and voltage solutions in Section §4. These computations rely on a Green's function representation of solutions. We find that ionic concentrations at the influx location deviate from local electro-neutrality (§4.2), but that these deviations become negligible as the Debye length shrinks (§4.3). In Section §5 we provide numerical simulations on spheroid domains, deforming spheres into prolate or oblate spheroids to study how voltage dynamics is modulated by the local membrane curvature, for the case of two and three ionic charges. Finally, Section §6 discusses the present computation in the context of neuroscience, with a few open mathematical problems mentioned.

# 2 Main result summary 

The main result of this article is summarized as follows: we obtain relations between ionic densities, voltage, and an influx current composed of single cation $\left(z_{1}>0\right)$. The bounded domain $\Omega$ (Fig. 1) is of characteristic length-scale

$$
R=\frac{1}{2} \max \{\|\boldsymbol{x}-\boldsymbol{y}\| \mid \boldsymbol{x}, \boldsymbol{y} \in \partial \Omega\}
$$

with an isoperimetric ratio satisfying $|\partial \Omega| /|\Omega|^{2 / 3} \sim O(1)$. The boundary $\partial \Omega$ contains two narrow disk channels $\partial \Omega_{A_{1}}, \partial \Omega_{A_{2}}$ of radii $A_{1}, A_{2} \ll R$, centered in $\boldsymbol{x}_{1}, \boldsymbol{x}_{2}$, which receive and emit ionic fluxes. The mean membrane curvature in $\boldsymbol{x} \in \partial \Omega$ is given by $H(\boldsymbol{x})$ and $\alpha$ is the ratio

$$
\alpha=\frac{R}{\lambda_{D}}
$$

between R and the Debye length $\lambda_{D}$. With the above domain characteristics, we use the electro-diffusion model to obtain the following results:
![img-0.jpeg](img-0.jpeg)

Figure 1: Domain schematic diagram. Example of an ellipsoid-shaped domain $\Omega$ of length-scale $R$. A positive-charge influx current is sent through a first narrow window $\partial \Omega_{A_{1}}$, while on $\partial \Omega_{A_{2}}$ ionic concentrations are set to be constant.

Small charge regime: $\alpha \sim O(1)$. The ionic and voltage solutions are given at the influx location by

$$
\begin{aligned}
c_{1}\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{1}\right)= & C_{1}+\frac{I}{z_{1} \mathcal{F} D_{1} \pi A_{2}}\left(\frac{A_{2}}{A_{1}}-\frac{H\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{1}\right)}{4} A_{2} \log \left(\frac{A_{1}}{R}\right)\right. \\
& \left.+\left(1-\frac{z_{1}^{2} C_{1}}{\sum_{k=1}^{n} z_{k}^{2} C_{k}}\right)\left(\frac{\pi}{4}-\frac{H\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{2}\right)}{4} A_{2} \log \left(\frac{A_{2}}{R}\right)\right)+O\left(\frac{A_{2}}{R}\right)\right) \\
c_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{1}\right)= & C_{i}-z_{i} C_{i}\left(\frac{I}{\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n} z_{k}^{2} C_{k}\right) \mathcal{F} D_{1} \pi A_{2}}\left(\frac{\pi}{4}-\frac{H\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{2}\right)}{4} A_{2} \log \left(\frac{A_{2}}{R}\right)+O\left(\frac{A_{2}}{R}\right)\right)\right), \quad i \neq 1 \\
v\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{1}\right)= & \frac{k_{B} \mathcal{T}}{e}\left(\frac{I}{\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n} z_{k}^{2} C_{k}\right) \mathcal{F} D_{1} \pi A_{2}}\left(\frac{\pi}{4}-\frac{H\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{2}\right)}{4} A_{2} \log \left(\frac{A_{2}}{R}\right)+O\left(\frac{A_{2}}{R}\right)\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where we have the Faraday constant $\mathcal{F}$, thermal voltage $\frac{k_{B} \mathcal{T}}{e}$, valence $z_{i}$ and fixed ionic densities $C_{i}$ on the exit. Note that $H\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{1}\right)$ and $H\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{2}\right)$ are the mean boundary curvature at the center of the narrow windows $\partial \Omega_{A_{1}}, \partial \Omega_{A_{2}}$ (Fig. 1) and that we impose the local electro-neutrality condition

$$
\sum_{i=1}^{n} z_{i} C_{i}=0
$$

Large charge regime: $\alpha \gg 1$. The solutions Eq. (2.3) become

$$
\begin{aligned}
c_{1}\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{1}\right) & =C_{1}+\frac{I F\left(A_{1}, A_{2}, R\right)}{z_{1} \mathcal{F} D_{1} \pi A_{2}} \\
c_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{1}\right) & =C_{i}-z_{i} C_{i}\left(\frac{I F\left(A_{1}, A_{2}, R\right)}{\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n} z_{k}^{2} C_{k}\right) \mathcal{F} D_{1} \pi A_{2}}\right), \quad i \neq 1 \\
v\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{1}\right) & =\frac{k_{B} \mathcal{T}}{e}\left(\frac{I F\left(A_{1}, A_{2}, R\right)}{\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n} z_{k}^{2} C_{k}\right) \mathcal{F} D_{1} \pi A_{2}}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where

$$
F\left(A_{1}, A_{2}, R\right)=\frac{A_{2}}{A_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4}-\frac{A_{2}}{4}\left(H\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{1}\right) \log \left(\frac{A_{1}}{R}\right)+H\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{2}\right) \log \left(\frac{A_{2}}{R}\right)\right)+O\left(\frac{A_{2}}{R}\right)
$$

For two-charge models with monovalent ionic species, or more generally if $z_{2}=-1$, the voltage is given by

$$
v\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{1}\right)=\frac{k_{B} \mathcal{T}}{e} \log \left(1+\frac{I F\left(A_{1}, A_{2}, R\right)}{\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n} z_{k}^{2} C_{k}\right) \mathcal{F} D_{1} \pi A_{2}}\right)
$$

# 3 PNP electro-diffusion model with multiple ionic charges 

We describe here the Poisson-Nernst-Planck (PNP) model which consists of the Poisson's equation for the voltage $v(\boldsymbol{x}, t)$ generated by the local ionic concentration differences, and the Fokker-Planck equations describing the motion of charged particles within the induced electric field. The ionic system within the bounded domain $\Omega$ involves multiple species, each of density $c_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}, t)$ and valence $z_{i}$ for $i=1, \ldots, n$, with the corresponding electro-chemical gradient flux

$$
j_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}, t)=-D_{i}\left(\nabla c_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}, t)+\frac{z_{i} e}{k_{B} \mathcal{T}} c_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}, t) \nabla v(\boldsymbol{x}, t)\right), \quad i=1, \ldots, n
$$

where $D_{i}$ is the diffusion coefficient while $k_{B} \mathcal{T} / e \approx 26 \mathrm{mV}$ is the thermal voltage. The Nernst-Planck equation for each $i=1, \ldots, n$ is

$$
\frac{\partial c_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}, t)}{\partial t}=-\nabla \cdot j_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}, t)=D_{i}\left(\Delta c_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}, t)+\frac{z_{i} e}{k_{B} \mathcal{T}} \nabla\left(c_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}, t) \nabla v(\boldsymbol{x}, t)\right)\right), \quad \boldsymbol{x} \in \Omega, \quad t>0
$$

while the voltage $v(\boldsymbol{x}, t)$ is solution of the Poisson's equation

$$
\Delta v(\boldsymbol{x}, t)+\frac{\mathcal{F}}{\varepsilon \varepsilon_{0}} \sum_{i=1}^{n} z_{i} c_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}, t)=0, \quad \boldsymbol{x} \in \Omega, \quad t>0
$$

with Faraday constant $\mathcal{F}$ and electrical permittivity $\varepsilon \varepsilon_{0}$.

### 3.1 Boundary conditions

We model the inward and outward ionic fluxes through membrane-bound protein channels, that are approximated as narrow disks on the boundary $\partial \Omega_{A_{1}}$ and $\partial \Omega_{A_{2}}$, of radius $A_{1}, A_{2}$ and centered in $\boldsymbol{x}_{1}, \boldsymbol{x}_{2}$. The first window receives an ionic influx of species $c_{1}(\boldsymbol{x}, t)$ only, whose valence $z_{1}$ is positive to model the injection of cations within a neuronal nano-domain, while on the exit site we impose constant ionic densities. Thus on $\partial \Omega_{A_{1}}$ we have the following (Neumann) flux boundary condition,

$$
\boldsymbol{n} \cdot j_{1}(\boldsymbol{x}, t)+\frac{I}{z_{1} \mathcal{F} \pi A_{1}^{2}}=0, \quad \boldsymbol{n} \cdot j_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}, t)=0, \quad \boldsymbol{x} \in \partial \Omega_{A_{1}}, \quad i=2, \ldots, n
$$

where $\boldsymbol{n}$ is the outward unit vector to $\partial \Omega$. On $\partial \Omega_{A_{2}}$ we set each ionic densities to be constant, with the rest of the boundary $\partial \Omega_{r}=\partial \Omega \backslash\left\{\partial \Omega_{A_{1}} \cap \partial \Omega_{A_{2}}\right\}$ that is fully reflecting to all ions, thus yielding

$$
c_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}, t)=C_{i}, \quad \boldsymbol{x} \in \partial \Omega_{A_{2}}, \quad \boldsymbol{n} \cdot j_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}, t)=0, \quad \boldsymbol{x} \in \partial \Omega_{r}, \quad i=1, \ldots, n
$$

to which we add the local electro-neutrality condition,

$$
\sum_{i=1}^{n} z_{i} C_{i}=0
$$

Lastly the boundary conditions for the voltage is imposed on the exit site $\partial \Omega_{A_{2}}$ as ground condition, while everywhere else we neglect the capacitance of the membrane and set to zero the component of the electric field normal to the boundary, leading to

$$
\boldsymbol{x} \in \partial \Omega_{A_{2}}, \quad \boldsymbol{n} \cdot \nabla v(\boldsymbol{x}, t)=0, \quad \boldsymbol{x} \in \partial \Omega \backslash \partial \Omega_{A_{2}}, \quad v(\boldsymbol{x}, t)=0
$$

# 3.2 Non-dimensionalization 

We show here how we use the dimensional spatial $\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}$ and time $\tilde{t}$ variables:

$$
\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}=\frac{\boldsymbol{x}}{R} \in \tilde{\Omega}, \quad \tilde{t}=\frac{D_{1}}{R^{2}} t
$$

where $D_{1}$ is the diffusion coefficient of the first ionic species, while $\tilde{\Omega}=\Omega / R$ is the rescaled domain. The weighted sum $\sum_{k=1}^{n} z_{k}^{2} C_{k}$ measures the conductivity of the electrolyte. By using this term and the thermal voltage $k_{B} \mathcal{T} / e$ we can define new density and voltage variables given by

$$
\tilde{c}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})=\frac{c_{i}\left(R \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \frac{R^{2}}{D_{1}} \tilde{t}\right)}{\sum_{k=1}^{n} z_{k}^{2} C_{k}}, \quad i=1, \ldots, n, \quad \tilde{v}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})=\frac{e}{k_{B} \mathcal{T}} v\left(R \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \frac{R^{2}}{D_{1}} \tilde{t}\right)
$$

as well as dimensionless electro-chemical gradients,

$$
\tilde{j}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})=\frac{R j_{i}\left(R \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \frac{R^{2}}{D_{1}} \tilde{t}\right)}{D_{i} \sum_{k=1}^{n} z_{k}^{2} C_{k}}=-\left(\nabla c_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})+z_{i} c_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t}) \nabla \tilde{v}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})\right), \quad i=1, \ldots, n
$$

Then, upon substituting within the PNP Eq. (3.2)-(3.4), we obtain

$$
\begin{gathered}
\tau_{i} \frac{\partial \tilde{c}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})}{\partial t}+\nabla \cdot \tilde{j}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})=0, \quad i=1, \ldots, n, \quad \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} \in \tilde{\Omega} \\
\Delta \tilde{v}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})+\alpha^{2} \sum_{i=1}^{n} z_{i} \tilde{c}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})=0, \quad \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} \in \tilde{\Omega}
\end{gathered}
$$

where $\tau_{i}=D_{1} / D_{i}$ is a diffusion coefficients ratio while $\alpha$ is given by

$$
\alpha=\frac{R}{\lambda_{D}}, \quad \text { with } \quad \lambda_{D}=\sqrt{\frac{k_{B} \mathcal{T} \varepsilon \varepsilon_{0}}{e \mathcal{F} \sum_{k=1}^{n} z_{k}^{2} C_{k}}}
$$

and thus it corresponds to the ratio of the domain length-scale $R$ over the Debye length $\lambda_{D}$ measuring electro-static interaction lengths in the absence of external flux. The boundary conditions Eq. (3.4) get reformulated as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \boldsymbol{n} \cdot \tilde{j}_{1}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})+\frac{J}{z_{1}}=0, \quad \boldsymbol{n} \cdot \tilde{c}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})=0, \quad i=2, \ldots, n, \quad \boldsymbol{n} \cdot \tilde{v}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})=0, \quad \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} \in \partial \tilde{\Omega}_{a_{1}} \\
& \tilde{c}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})=\nu_{i}, \quad i=1, \ldots, n, \quad \tilde{v}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})=0, \quad \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} \in \partial \tilde{\Omega}_{a_{2}} \\
& \boldsymbol{n} \cdot \tilde{j}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})=0, \quad i=1, \ldots, n, \quad \boldsymbol{n} \cdot \tilde{v}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}, \tilde{t})=0, \quad \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} \in \partial \tilde{\Omega}_{r}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\partial \tilde{\Omega}_{a_{1}}$ and $\partial \tilde{\Omega}_{a_{2}}$ are two small circular windows of radii $a_{1}=A_{1} / R$ and $a_{2}=A_{2} / R$, centered in $\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}=\boldsymbol{x}_{1} / R$ and $\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}=\boldsymbol{x}_{2} / R$. In Eq. (3.10) the parameter $J$ measures the strength of the influx current entering window $\partial \tilde{\Omega}_{a_{1}}$, while $\nu_{i}$ for each $i$ is proportional to the exit site $\partial \tilde{\Omega}_{a_{2}}$ constant ionic density:

$$
J=\frac{I R}{\mathcal{F} \pi A_{1}^{2} D_{1}\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n} z_{k}^{2} C_{k}\right)}, \quad \nu_{i}=\frac{C_{i}}{\sum_{k=1}^{n} z_{k}^{2} C_{k}}, \quad i=1, \ldots, n
$$

We seek solutions for the ionic densities $\tilde{c}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}})$ and voltage $\tilde{v}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}})$ distribution at steady-state, thus satisfying

$$
\begin{gathered}
\nabla \cdot \tilde{j}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}})=\Delta \tilde{c}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}})+z_{i} \nabla \cdot\left(\tilde{c}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}) \nabla \tilde{v}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}})\right)=0, \quad \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} \in \tilde{\Omega} \\
\Delta \tilde{v}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}})+\alpha^{2} \sum_{i=1}^{n} z_{i} \tilde{c}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}})=0, \quad \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} \in \tilde{\Omega}
\end{gathered}
$$

for two different parameter regimes: first $\alpha \sim O(1)$, and then $\alpha \gg 1$. For the first case the Debye length is of the order of the domain length-scale, while for the latter $\lambda_{D}$ is much smaller than $R$. Lengthscales of neuronal nano-compartments are usually of the order of hundreds of nanometers (with $R=500$ nm for a typical dendritic spine head), while for a 1:1 binary electrolyte with steady-state ionic density $C_{1}=C_{2}=100 \mathrm{mM}$, we calculate $\lambda_{D} \approx 1 \mathrm{~nm}$. Thus in practice $\alpha \gg 1$, but we will show that our analysis can also treat the case $\alpha \sim O(1)$ corresponding to small interior charge densities. The two distinct cases can be handled by introducing the coordinate $\boldsymbol{\xi}=\alpha \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}$ within the stretched domain $\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}=\alpha \tilde{\Omega}$, but we remark that this is the same as rescaling $\boldsymbol{x} \in \Omega$ by the Debye length, with $\boldsymbol{\xi}=\boldsymbol{x} / \lambda_{D}$. Upon defining new density and voltage variables as

$$
\mathcal{C}_{i}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=\tilde{c}_{i}(\boldsymbol{\xi} / \alpha), \quad i=1, \ldots, n, \quad \mathcal{V}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=\tilde{v}(\boldsymbol{\xi} / \alpha)
$$

we can reformulate (3.12) as

$$
\begin{gathered}
\Delta \mathcal{C}_{i}(\boldsymbol{\xi})+z_{i} \nabla\left(\mathcal{C}_{i}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) \nabla \mathcal{V}(\boldsymbol{\xi})\right)=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}} \\
\Delta \mathcal{V}(\boldsymbol{\xi})+\sum_{i=1}^{n} z_{i} \mathcal{C}_{i}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}
\end{gathered}
$$

subject to the boundary conditions

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\partial \mathcal{C}_{1}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=\frac{J}{\alpha z_{1}}, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{C}_{i}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}} & =0, \quad i=2, \ldots, n, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{V}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}} \\
\mathcal{C}_{i}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) & =\nu_{i}, \quad i=1, \ldots, n, \quad \mathcal{V}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}} \\
\frac{\partial \mathcal{C}_{i}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}} & =0, \quad i=1, \ldots, n, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{V}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{r}}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}}$ for $j=1,2$ are two circular boundary disks of radius $\alpha a_{j}$ centered in $\boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}$ on $\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}$. Note that the ratio $\frac{J}{\alpha}$ is the single parameter controlling the strength of the influx and the electric potential due to ionic density disturbances.

# 4 Introducing a regular asymptotic expansion 

To derive an approximate solution to system Eq. (3.14), we introduce a regular asymptotic expansion in terms of the ratio $\frac{J}{\alpha}$ around the background steady-state and locally electro-neutral ionic solutions,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathcal{C}_{i}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=\nu_{i}+\mathcal{C}_{i}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) \frac{J}{\alpha}+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right), \quad i=1, \ldots, n \\
& \mathcal{V}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=\mathcal{V}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) \frac{J}{\alpha}+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

which is valid assuming $J \ll \alpha$. Thus when $\alpha \sim O(1)$ with the Debye length of the order of the domain length-scale, we must have $J \ll 1$. Alternatively if $\alpha \gg 1$ the expansion (4.1) will also hold for a current $J$ of order one, with $J \sim O(1)$. By collecting terms at order $O\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)$ we get the following linearized problem,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \Delta \mathcal{C}_{i}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})+z_{i} \nu_{i} \Delta \mathcal{V}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}} \\
& \Delta \mathcal{V}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})+\sum_{i=1}^{n} z_{i} \mathcal{C}_{i}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}
\end{aligned}
$$

along with the boundary conditions

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{\partial \mathcal{C}_{1}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=\frac{1}{z_{1}}, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{C}_{i}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=0, \quad i=2, \ldots, n, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{V}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}} \\
\mathcal{C}_{i}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad i=1, \ldots, n, \quad \mathcal{V}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}} \\
\frac{\partial \mathcal{C}_{i}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=0, \quad i=1, \ldots, n, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{V}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{r}}
\end{gathered}
$$

We solve this system by introducing the intermediate functions below

$$
\mathcal{S}_{i j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=z_{j} \nu_{j} \mathcal{C}_{i}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})-z_{i} \nu_{i} \mathcal{C}_{j}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi}), \quad \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=\sum_{i=1}^{n} z_{i} \mathcal{C}_{i}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})
$$

where we note that $\mathcal{S}_{i j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=-\mathcal{S}_{j i}(\boldsymbol{\xi})$ and $\mathcal{S}_{i i}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0$, and with $\mathcal{S}_{i j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})$ and $\mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})$ satisfying

$$
\Delta \mathcal{S}_{i j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad \Delta \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})-\mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0
$$

Next, boundary conditions then are established by considering the different indices $i, j$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\partial \mathcal{S}_{1 j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=\frac{z_{j} \nu_{j}}{z_{1}}, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}, \quad \mathcal{S}_{1 j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{S}_{1 j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{r}}, \quad j \neq 1 \\
& \frac{\partial \mathcal{S}_{j 1}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=-\frac{z_{j} \nu_{j}}{z_{1}}, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}, \quad \mathcal{S}_{j 1}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{S}_{j 1}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{r}}, \quad j \neq 1 \\
& \frac{\partial \mathcal{S}_{i j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}, \quad \mathcal{S}_{i j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{S}_{i j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{r}}, \quad i \neq 1, j \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

from which we easily establish that $\mathcal{S}_{i j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0$ when both $i \neq 1$ and $j \neq 1$. We then find that the function $\mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})$ has the boundary condition

$$
\frac{\partial \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=1, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}, \quad \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{r}}
$$

Although fluxes through the exit $\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}$ are unknown, we show in Appendix §A. 2 that they can be approximated by the classical Weber solution [32],

$$
\frac{\partial \mathcal{S}_{1 j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=\frac{\mathcal{K}_{1 j}}{\sqrt{\left(\alpha a_{2}\right)^{2}-\left\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right\|^{2}}}, \quad j \neq 1, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=\frac{\mathcal{K}}{\sqrt{\left(\alpha a_{2}\right)^{2}-\left\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right\|^{2}}}, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}
$$

where the constants $\mathcal{K}_{1 j}$ and $\mathcal{K}$ are evaluated upon applying the divergence theorem to Eq. (4.4) and (4.5),

$$
\begin{gathered}
\pi\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} \frac{z_{j} \nu_{j}}{z_{1}}+2 \pi \mathcal{K}_{1 j} \alpha a_{2}=0 \\
\pi\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2}+2 \pi \mathcal{K} \alpha a_{2}-\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right| \overline{\mathcal{P}}=0
\end{gathered}
$$

yielding

$$
\mathcal{K}_{1 j}=-\frac{\alpha a_{1}^{2} z_{j} \nu_{j}}{2 a_{2} z_{1}}, \quad \mathcal{K}=\frac{\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right| \overline{\mathcal{P}}}{2 \pi \alpha a_{2}}-\frac{\alpha a_{1}^{2}}{2 a_{2}}
$$

We solve the system (4.4) with the Green's function $\mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta})$ (Appendix §A.1) solution of

$$
\Delta \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta})=\frac{1}{\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|}, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=\delta(\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\eta}), \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}, \quad \int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta}) d \boldsymbol{\xi}=0 \quad \boldsymbol{\eta} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}
$$

Upon applying Green's second identity to the systems (4.4) and (4.9), we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{S}_{1 j}(\boldsymbol{\eta}) & =\overline{\mathcal{S}_{1 j}}+\int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta}) \frac{\partial \mathcal{S}_{1 j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}} d \boldsymbol{\xi}+\int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta}) \frac{\partial \mathcal{S}_{1 j}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}} d \boldsymbol{\xi} \\
\mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\eta}) & =\overline{\mathcal{P}}+\int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta}) \frac{\partial \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}} d \boldsymbol{\xi}+\int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta}) \frac{\partial \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}} d \boldsymbol{\xi}-\int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta}) \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\overline{\mathcal{S}_{1 j}}$ and $\overline{\mathcal{P}}$ indicate domain averages,

$$
\overline{\mathcal{S}_{1 j}}=\frac{1}{\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|} \int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}} \mathcal{S}_{1 j}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi}, \quad \overline{\mathcal{P}}=\frac{1}{\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|} \int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}} \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi}
$$

and then after substituting $\boldsymbol{\eta}=\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}$ and using the absorbing boundary conditions $\mathcal{S}_{1 j}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)=\mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)=0$, we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{S}_{1 j}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) & =\overline{\mathcal{S}_{1 j}}+\frac{z_{j} \nu_{j}}{z_{1}} \int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi}+\mathcal{K}_{1 j} \int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}} \frac{\mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{\sqrt{\left(\alpha a_{2}\right)^{2}-\left\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right\|^{2}}} d \boldsymbol{\xi} \\
0 & =\overline{\mathcal{S}_{1 j}}+\frac{z_{j} \nu_{j}}{z_{1}} \int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi}+\mathcal{K}_{1 j} \int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}} \frac{\mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{\sqrt{\left(\alpha a_{2}\right)^{2}-\left\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right\|^{2}}} d \boldsymbol{\xi} \\
\mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) & =\overline{\mathcal{P}}+\int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi}+\mathcal{K} \int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}} \frac{\mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{\sqrt{\left(\alpha a_{2}\right)^{2}-\left\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right\|^{2}}} d \boldsymbol{\xi}-\int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi} \\
0 & =\overline{\mathcal{P}}+\int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi}+\mathcal{K} \int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}} \frac{\mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{\sqrt{\left(\alpha a_{2}\right)^{2}-\left\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right\|^{2}}} d \boldsymbol{\xi}-\int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi}
\end{aligned}
$$

These integrals involving the Neumann Green's function are evaluated in Appendix §A.3, where we get the linear system of equations below for $\mathcal{S}_{1 j}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right), \overline{\mathcal{S}_{1 j}}, \mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)$ and $\overline{\mathcal{P}}$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{S}_{1 j}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) & =\overline{\mathcal{S}_{1 j}}+\frac{z_{j} \nu_{j}}{z_{1}} a_{1} \alpha f\left(a_{1}\right)+2 \pi \mathcal{K}_{1 j} a_{2} \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \\
0 & =\overline{\mathcal{S}_{1 j}}+\frac{z_{j} \nu_{j}}{z_{1}} \pi\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)+\mathcal{K}_{1 j} \frac{\pi}{2} g\left(a_{2}\right) \\
\mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) & =\overline{\mathcal{P}}+a_{1} \alpha f\left(a_{1}\right)+2 \pi \mathcal{K} a_{2} \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)-\mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} m\left(a_{1}\right) \\
0 & =\overline{\mathcal{P}}+\pi\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)+\mathcal{K} \frac{\pi}{2} g\left(a_{2}\right)-\mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \alpha^{3} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

and then upon substituting expressions for $\mathcal{K}_{1 j}$ and $\mathcal{K}$ from Eq. (4.8) we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{S}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)-\overline{\mathcal{S}_{1 j}} & =\frac{z_{j} \nu_{j}}{z_{1}} \alpha a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right) \\
\overline{\mathcal{S}_{1 j}} & =\frac{z_{j} \nu_{j}}{z_{1}} \alpha a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right) \\
\left(1+\frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} m\left(a_{1}\right)\right) \mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)-\left(1+\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right| \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right) \overline{\mathcal{P}} & =\alpha a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right) \\
-\frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \alpha^{3} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) \mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)+\left(1+\left.\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 \alpha a_{2}} \right\rvert\, \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}} \right\rvert\,\right) \overline{\mathcal{P}}=\alpha a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Here $f\left(a_{1}\right), g\left(a_{2}\right)$ and $m\left(a_{1}\right)$ are expansions of the narrow window radii $a_{1}$ and $a_{2}$, given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
f\left(a_{1}\right) & =1-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4} a_{1} \log \left(a_{1}\right)+\alpha a_{1}\left(\pi \mathcal{R}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)+\frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4}\left(\frac{1}{2}-\log (\alpha)\right)\right)+O\left(a_{1}^{2}\right) \\
g\left(a_{2}\right) & =1-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{\pi} a_{2} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+\alpha a_{2}\left(4 \mathcal{R}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)+\frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{\pi}(1-\log (2)-\log (\alpha))\right)+O\left(a_{2}^{2}\right) \\
m\left(a_{1}\right) & =1-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{3} a_{1} \log \left(a_{1}\right)+\alpha a_{1}\left(\frac{4 \pi}{3} \mathcal{R}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)+\frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{3}\left(\frac{1}{3}-\log (\alpha)\right)\right)+O\left(a_{1}^{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Upon solving the system Eq. (4.14) we find that $\mathcal{S}_{1 j}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)$ and $\overline{\mathcal{S}_{1 j}}$ are given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{S}_{1 j}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) & =\frac{z_{j} \nu_{j}}{z_{1}} a_{1}^{2} \alpha\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-2 \pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\right) \\
\overline{\mathcal{S}}_{1 j} & =\frac{z_{j} \nu_{j}}{z_{1}} a_{1}^{2} \alpha\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \pi \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

while for $\mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)$ and $\overline{\mathcal{P}}$ we have

$$
\mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)=\alpha a_{1}^{2} \mathcal{A}, \quad \overline{\mathcal{P}}=\alpha a_{1}^{2} \mathcal{B}
$$

where $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ are two fractions

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathcal{A}=\frac{\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right)\left(1+\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 \alpha a_{2}}\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|\right)+\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right)\left(1+\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right| \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right)}{\left(1+\frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} m\left(a_{1}\right)\right)\left(1+\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 \alpha a_{2}}\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|\right)-\left(1+\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right| \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \alpha^{3} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)} \\
\mathcal{B}=\frac{\left(1+\frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} m\left(a_{1}\right)\right)\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right)+\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \alpha^{3} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{\left(1+\frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} m\left(a_{1}\right)\right)\left(1+\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 \alpha a_{2}}\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|\right)-\left(1+\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right| \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \alpha^{3} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}
\end{gathered}
$$

To recover the perturbation terms at $O\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)$ we simply need to calculate

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathcal{C}_{1}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=z_{1} \nu_{1} \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})+\sum_{j=2}^{n} z_{j} \mathcal{S}_{1 j}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) \\
& \mathcal{C}_{i}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=z_{i} \nu_{i} \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})-z_{1} \mathcal{S}_{1 i}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

At the influx location this yields

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathcal{C}_{1}^{(1)}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)=z_{1} \nu_{1} a_{1}^{2} \alpha\left(\mathcal{A}+\left(\frac{1}{z_{1}^{2} \nu_{1}}-1\right)\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-2 \pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\right)\right) \\
& \mathcal{C}_{i}^{(1)}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)=z_{i} \nu_{i} a_{1}^{2} \alpha\left(\mathcal{A}-\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-2 \pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\right)\right), \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

while for the averages we find

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \overline{\mathcal{C}_{1}^{(1)}}=z_{1} \nu_{1} a_{1}^{2} \alpha\left(\mathcal{B}+\left(\frac{1}{z_{1}^{2} \nu_{1}}-1\right)\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\right)\right) \\
& \overline{\mathcal{C}_{i}^{(1)}}=z_{i} \nu_{i} a_{1}^{2} \alpha\left(\mathcal{B}-\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\right)\right), \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

Finally we have the first-order approximations for ionic densities at the influx location

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathcal{C}_{1}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)=\nu_{1}+J z_{1} \nu_{1} a_{1}^{2}\left(\mathcal{A}+\left(\frac{1}{z_{1}^{2} \nu_{1}}-1\right)\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-2 \pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\right)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \mathcal{C}_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)=\nu_{i}+J z_{i} \nu_{i} a_{1}^{2}\left(\mathcal{A}-\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-2 \pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\right)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right), \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

as well as averages given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \overline{\mathcal{C}_{1}}=\nu_{1}+J z_{1} \nu_{1} a_{1}^{2}\left(\mathcal{B}+\left(\frac{1}{z_{1}^{2} \nu_{1}}-1\right)\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\right)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \overline{\mathcal{C}_{i}}=\nu_{i}+J z_{i} \nu_{i} a_{1}^{2}\left(\mathcal{B}-\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\right)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right), \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

# 4.1 Asymptotic solution for the voltage 

We proceed by finding a first-order voltage solution. At $O\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)$ we have

$$
\Delta \mathcal{V}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=-\mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}), \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}, \quad \mathcal{V}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{V}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=0, \quad \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}} \backslash \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}
$$

with Green's identity that yields

$$
\mathcal{V}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\eta})=\overline{\mathcal{V}^{(1)}}+\int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta}) \frac{\partial \mathcal{V}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}} d \boldsymbol{\xi}+\int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta}) \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi}
$$

where $\overline{\mathcal{V}^{(1)}}$ corresponds to the domain average as in Eq. (4.11). Here also we can use Weber's solution to approximate the flux through $\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}$,

$$
\frac{\partial \mathcal{V}^{(1)}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=\frac{\mathcal{K}}{\sqrt{\left(\alpha a_{2}\right)^{2}-\left\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right\|^{2}}}, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}, \quad \text { with } \quad \mathcal{K}=-\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right| \frac{\overline{\mathcal{P}}}{2 \pi \alpha a_{2}}
$$

where the constraint on $\mathcal{K}$ is obtained by applying the divergence theorem to Eq. (4.29). By then setting $\boldsymbol{\eta}=\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}$ within Eq. (4.30) we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{V}^{(1)}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) & =\overline{\mathcal{V}^{(1)}}+2 \pi a_{2} \mathcal{K} \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} m\left(a_{1}\right) \mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \\
0 & =\overline{\mathcal{V}^{(1)}}+\mathcal{K} \frac{\pi}{2} g\left(a_{2}\right)+\frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \alpha^{3} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) \mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

which becomes,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{V}^{(1)}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)-\overline{\mathcal{V}^{(1)}} & =\alpha a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} m\left(a_{1}\right) \mathcal{A}-\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right| \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \mathcal{B}\right) \\
\overline{\mathcal{V}^{(1)}} & =\alpha a_{1}^{2}\left(\left.\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 \alpha a_{2}}\right|_{\Omega} \boldsymbol{\xi}\right) \mathcal{B}-\frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \alpha^{3} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) \mathcal{A}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

after using Eq. (4.31) with $\mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)=\alpha a_{1}^{2} \mathcal{A}$ and $\overline{\mathcal{P}}=\alpha a_{1}^{2} \mathcal{B}$. The solution to this system is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{V}^{(1)}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) & =\alpha a_{1}^{2}\left(\left(m\left(a_{1}\right)-\frac{4 \pi}{3} a_{1} \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\right) \frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} \mathcal{A}+\left(\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|}{\alpha} \mathcal{B}\right) \\
\overline{\mathcal{V}^{(1)}} & =\alpha a_{1}^{2}\left(\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right| \frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 \alpha a_{2}} \mathcal{B}-\frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \alpha^{3} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) \mathcal{A}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

and then the first-order approximation becomes

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{V}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) & =J a_{1}^{2}\left(\left(m\left(a_{1}\right)-\frac{4 \pi}{3} a_{1} \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\right) \frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} \mathcal{A}+\left(\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|}{\alpha} \mathcal{B}\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
\overline{\mathcal{V}} & =J a_{1}^{2}\left(\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right| \frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 \alpha a_{2}} \mathcal{B}-\frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \alpha^{3} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) \mathcal{A}\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

# 4.2 Small interior charge parameter regime 

We now derive refined asymptotic approximations for the charge densities and voltage valid when $\alpha \sim O(1)$, with the Debye length that is of the same order as the domain characteristic length-scale. Thus for the expansion parameter to be small we must have a small current $J$, and then combined with the narrow window limit this yields the following parameter regime,

$$
\alpha \sim O(1), \quad J \ll 1, \quad a_{1} \ll 1, \quad a_{2} \ll 1
$$

Upon expanding the ratios $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ in terms of the narrow window radii and neglecting terms of order $O(1)$ and beyond, we find in Appendix $\S$ B. 1 that

$$
\mathcal{A} \approx \frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi \alpha}{\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|} \approx \frac{1}{a_{1}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)+O(1), \quad \mathcal{B} \approx \frac{\pi \alpha}{\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|} \sim O(1)
$$

and thus the ionic charge densities in Eq. (4.27) become

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathcal{C}_{1}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \approx \nu_{1}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{z_{1}}\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)+\left(1-z_{1}^{2} \nu_{1}\right)\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \mathcal{C}_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \approx \nu_{i}-J z_{i} \nu_{i} a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right), \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

while for the average ionic densities we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \overline{\mathcal{C}_{1}} \approx \nu_{1}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{z_{1}}\left(1-z_{1}^{2} \nu_{1}\right)\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \overline{\mathcal{C}_{i}} \approx \nu_{i}-J z_{i} \nu_{i} a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right), \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

Also by performing an asymptotic reduction assuming $a_{1}, a_{2} \ll 1$ we find in Appendix $\S$ B. 1 the exact same current-voltage linear relation at the influx location and for the domain average,

$$
\mathcal{V}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)=\overline{\mathcal{V}} \approx J a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)
$$

Interestingly this equation can be recovered by using the classical Boltzmann solution

$$
\mathcal{V}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=-\frac{1}{z_{i}} \log \left(\frac{\mathcal{C}_{i}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\nu_{i}}\right)=\log \left(\left(\frac{\mathcal{C}_{i}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\nu_{i}}\right)^{-\frac{1}{z_{i}}}\right), \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}, \quad i \neq 1
$$

which is exact except for the first ion that is injected into the domain. We then set $\boldsymbol{\xi}=\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}$ and substitute the expansion in Eq. (4.39) to get

$$
\mathcal{V}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)=\log \left(\left(1-J z_{i} a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)\right)^{-1 / z_{i}}\right), \quad i \neq 1
$$

but then since $J a_{1}^{2} \ll 1$ we can use the binomial expansion to remove the dependence on the valence $z_{i}$

$$
\mathcal{V}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \approx \log \left(1+J a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)\right)
$$

while with one last Taylor expansion step we recover Eq. (4.42). We conclude this section with a summary of ionic and voltage formulas on the domain $\tilde{\Omega}$.
Principal Result 1 We consider a steady-state Poisson-Nernst-Planck electro-diffusion model with multiple ionic species $\tilde{c}_{i}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}})$ of valence $z_{i}$ in a bounded domain $\tilde{\Omega}$, with order one volume $|\tilde{\Omega}| \sim O(1)$ and mean boundary curvature function $\tilde{H}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}})$ with $\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} \in \partial \tilde{\Omega}$. Assume that a single charge $\tilde{c}_{1}(\boldsymbol{x})$ of positive valence $z_{1}>0$ is injected within the domain through a first narrow circular window $\partial \tilde{\Omega}_{a_{1}}$ while it exits via a second window $\partial \tilde{\Omega}_{a_{2}}$. Each window has radius $a_{j} \ll 1$ and is centered in $\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{j} \in \partial \tilde{\Omega}$, with $l=\left\|\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}-\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right\| \sim O(1)$ as these windows are well-spaced. In the parameter regime $\alpha \sim O(1)$ with small influx current $J \ll 1$, then the regular asymptotic expansions below hold for ionic densities at the influx location,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \tilde{c}_{1}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)=\nu_{1}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{z_{1}}\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)+\left(1-z_{1}^{2} \nu_{1}\right)\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \tilde{c}_{i}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)=\nu_{i}-J z_{i} \nu_{i} a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right), \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

while expansions for spatial average densities $\overline{\tilde{c}_{i}}$ are given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \overline{\tilde{c}_{1}}=\nu_{1}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{z_{1}}\left(1-z_{1}^{2} \nu_{1}\right)\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \overline{\tilde{c}_{i}}=\nu_{i}-J z_{i} \nu_{i} a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right), \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

We further calculate that ionic concentrations at the influx location deviate from local electro-neutrality while global deviations are negligible, yielding

$$
\sum_{j=1}^{n} z_{j} \tilde{c}_{j}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right) \approx J a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)\right)+O\left(J a_{1}^{2}\right), \quad \sum_{j=1}^{n} z_{j} \overline{\tilde{c}_{j}} \sim O\left(J a_{1}^{2}\right)
$$

For the special case of a 1:1 electrolyte with $z_{1}=+1$ and $z_{2}=-1$ these expansions reduce to

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \tilde{c}_{1}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{2}\left(\frac{2}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{2} \log \left(a_{1}\right)-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \tilde{c}_{2}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

while for average ionic densities we get the exact same expansion,

$$
\overline{\tilde{c}_{1}}=\overline{\tilde{c}_{2}}=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)
$$

Finally in this parameter regime voltage and influx current are expected to vary linearly as for Ohm's law, with the voltage drop across the domain and its spatial averages having the same magnitude as revealed by the formula below,

$$
\tilde{v}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)=\overline{\tilde{v}}=J a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)
$$

# 4.3 Large interior charge parameter regime 

Alternatively in the regime $\alpha \gg 1$ we can neglect the contribution from the ratios $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ since we have (see Appendix B.2),

$$
\mathcal{A} \sim O\left(\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}\right), \quad \mathcal{B} \sim O\left(\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}\right)
$$

and then by using the approximation below

$$
\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-2 \pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) \approx \frac{1}{a_{1}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)
$$

we find the following formulas for ionic densities at the influx location

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathcal{C}_{1}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \approx \nu_{1}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{z_{1}}\left(1-z_{1}^{2} \nu_{1}\right)\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \mathcal{C}_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \approx \nu_{i}-J z_{i} \nu_{i} a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right), \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

while for the average concentrations we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \overline{\mathcal{C}_{1}} \approx \nu_{1}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{z_{1}}\left(1-z_{1}^{2} \nu_{1}\right)\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \overline{\mathcal{C}_{i}} \approx \nu_{i}-J z_{i} \nu_{i} a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right), \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

In Appendix B. 2 we also evaluate the voltage drop and spatial average to be approximated by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{V}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) & \approx J a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
\overline{\mathcal{V}} & \approx J a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

As in Section $\S 4.2$, the classical Boltzmann solution yields

$$
\mathcal{V}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)=\log \left(\left(\frac{\mathcal{C}_{i}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{\nu_{i}}\right)^{-\frac{1}{z_{i}}}\right), \quad i \neq 1
$$

and then by substituting Eq. (4.52b) we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{V}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)= & \log \left(\left(1-J z_{i} a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)\right.\right. \\
& \left.+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)\right)^{-\frac{1}{z_{i}}}, \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

The dependence upon the valence can be removed by using the binomial expansion,

$$
\mathcal{V}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)=\log \left(1+J a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)\right)
$$

and by expanding the log function we recover formula Eq. (4.54a). We conclude this section with a summary of ionic and voltage formulas on the domain $\tilde{\Omega}$ with order one length-scale when $\alpha \gg 1$.
Principal Result 2 In the regime $\alpha \gg 1$ with small influx current $J \ll 1$, then the regular asymptotic expansions below hold for ionic densities at the influx location,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \tilde{c}_{1}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)=\nu_{1}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{z_{1}}\left(1-z_{1}^{2} \nu_{1}\right)\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \tilde{c}_{i}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)=\nu_{i}-J z_{i} \nu_{i} a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right), \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

while expansions for spatial averages are given by,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \overline{\tilde{c}_{1}}=\nu_{1}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{z_{1}}\left(1-z_{1}^{2} \nu_{1}\right)\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \overline{\tilde{c}_{i}}=\nu_{i}-J z_{i} \nu_{i} a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right), \quad i \neq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

which are the same as for the $\alpha \sim O(1)$ regime. Deviations from local or global electro-neutrality are also found to be negligible, as shown upon evaluating the sums,

$$
\sum_{j=1}^{n} z_{j} \tilde{c}_{j}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right) \sim O\left(J a_{1}^{2}\right), \quad \sum_{j=1}^{n} z_{j} \overline{\tilde{c}_{j}} \sim O\left(J a_{1}^{2}\right)
$$

Furthermore, the special case of a 1:1 electrolyte yields the expansions below

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \tilde{c}_{1}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{2}\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
& \tilde{c}_{2}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{2}\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

while for ionic spatial averages we get

$$
\overline{\tilde{c}_{1}}=\overline{\tilde{c}_{2}}=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{J a_{1}^{2}}{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)
$$

In this regime we find that the total voltage drop across the domain $\tilde{v}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)$ differs from the average voltage $\overline{\tilde{v}}$, as shown by the asymptotic expansions

$$
\begin{aligned}
\tilde{v}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right) & =J a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right) \\
\overline{\tilde{v}} & =J a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

which holds for $J \ll 1$. For the special case of a 1:1 electrolyte, or more generally if $z_{2}=-1$, then a straightforward evaluation of Eq. (4.55a) yield a logarithmic current-voltage relationship,

$$
\tilde{v}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)=\log \left(1+J a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{a_{1}}+\frac{\pi}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+O(1)\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{J}{\alpha}\right)^{2}\right)\right)
$$

which also hold in the nonlinear regime.

# 5 Numerical simulations on spheroid domains 

In this section we perform full numerical simulations of the PNP electro-diffusion model defined in Eq. (3.2)(3.3), focusing on the $n=2,3$ ionic species case with results presented in terms of original dimensional variables. We also consider a class of spheroid domains $\Omega$ (Fig. 2) consisting of ellipsoid domains with azymuthal symmetry and axis described in the $x, y$ and $z$ directions by the set $\left(R_{1}, R_{1}, R_{2}\right)$. The case $R_{1}<R_{2}$ corresponds to a prolate spheroid (Fig. 2(a)), while $R_{1}>R_{2}$ yields an oblate spheroid (Fig. 2(c)) and with $R_{1}=R_{2}$ corresponding to a perfect sphere (Fig. 2(b)). We use the azymuth $\phi$ and the colatitude $\theta$ to parameterize the domain boundary as

$$
\partial \Omega=\left\{\left(R_{1} \cos (\phi) \sin (\theta), R_{1} \sin (\phi) \sin (\theta), R_{2} \cos (\theta)\right) \mid 0 \leq \phi<2 \pi, 0 \leq \theta \leq \pi\right\}
$$

but due to azymuthal invariance the mean curvature only depends on the colatitude $\theta$,

$$
H(\theta)=\frac{R_{2}\left(2 R_{1}^{2}+\left(R_{2}^{2}-R_{1}^{2}\right) \sin ^{2}(\theta)\right)}{2 R_{1}\left(R_{1}^{2}+\left(R_{2}^{2}-R_{1}^{2}\right) \sin ^{2}(\theta)\right)^{3 / 2}}
$$

which reduces to $H=1 / R_{1}$ when $R_{1}=R_{2}$. The characteristic length-scale of the dimensional domain $\Omega$ is further defined as $R=\max \left\{R_{1}, R_{2}\right\}$.
Here the simulations shown in Fig. 2 apply to voltage propagation within head compartments of dendritic spines following stimulation by a synaptic current [33], with these results confirming that these compartments are mostly equipotential $[28,30]$.

# 5.2 Domain geometry and membrane curvature 

We proceed by investigating how the domain, channels size and mean membrane curvature can affect voltage dynamics (Fig. 5-6) in the regime $\alpha \gg 1$. # 6 Discussion 

In this article we found I-V relations inside nanocellular electrolytes containing multiple ionic species. The voltage is modeled using electro-diffusion theory formulated with the PNP equations. After normalizing the main variables (dimensional scaling) in Section $\S 3$, we find two key parameters controlling how voltage spreads and drops within the nano-domain: the influx current $J$ and the ratio $\alpha=R / \lambda_{D}$ between the domain length-scale and the Debye length. A spatial rescaling with the Debye length then allows us to perform the computation based on a regular asymptotic expansion in terms of the small ratio $J / \alpha$ and solve for linearized ionic and voltage solutions at $O(J / \alpha)$ using Green's function methods in $\S 4$.
The main advantage of this expansion is to allow $\alpha$ to be of order one (with $R \sim \lambda_{D}$ ) or to be large with $\alpha \gg 1\left(R<\lambda_{D}\right)$. While the latter case leads to no significant deviation from electro-neutrality, we find that when $\alpha \sim O(1)$ ionic concentrations at the influx location deviate from local electro-neutrality with the maximal voltage drop well-approximated by the voltage domain average. The I-V formula derived here further reveals the role of the local mean membrane curvature in modulating ionic and voltage dynamics. Finally, numerical simulations illustrate how the curvature of three-dimensional prolate and oblate spheroid domains affect voltage and concentration distributions (Section §5).
It would be interesting to extend the current asymptotic theory to transient dynamical behaviors following a time-dependent influx. This would allow us to determine how recovery response time-scales are affected by membrane curvature and by the geometry of subcellular nanodomains.
