## A Computing boundary integrals with the Neumann Green's function
## A. 1 The Neumann Green's function

We start with the domain $\tilde{\Omega}$, of $O(1)$ characteristic length-scale, on which we can introduce the Neumann Green's function $\tilde{G}_{s}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{y}})$ solution of

$$
\Delta \tilde{G}_{s}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{y}})=\frac{1}{|\tilde{\Omega}|}, \quad \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} \in \tilde{\Omega}, \quad \frac{\partial \tilde{G}_{s}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{y}})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=\delta(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}-\tilde{\boldsymbol{y}}), \quad \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} \in \partial \tilde{\Omega}, \quad \int_{\tilde{\Omega}} \tilde{G}_{s}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{y}}) d \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}=0, \quad \tilde{\boldsymbol{y}} \in \partial \tilde{\Omega}
$$

that behaves near the singular diagonal $\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}=\tilde{\boldsymbol{y}}$ as

$$
\tilde{G}_{s}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{y}}) \approx \frac{1}{2 \pi\|\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}-\tilde{\boldsymbol{y}}\|}-\frac{\tilde{H}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{y}})}{4 \pi} \log (\|\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}-\tilde{\boldsymbol{y}}\|)+\tilde{R}_{s}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{y}}), \quad \text { with } \quad 0<\|\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}-\tilde{\boldsymbol{y}}\| \ll 1
$$

with mean boundary curvature function $\tilde{H}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{y}})$ and where $\tilde{R}_{s}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{y}})$ is the regular part, which can be further approximated as

$$
\tilde{R}_{s}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{y}}) \approx \tilde{R}_{s}(\tilde{\boldsymbol{y}} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{y}})+O(\|\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}-\tilde{\boldsymbol{y}}\|)
$$

However on the stretched domain $\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}$ with $\boldsymbol{\xi}=\alpha \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}$ and $\boldsymbol{\eta}=\alpha \tilde{\boldsymbol{y}}$, we can work with

$$
\mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta})=\frac{1}{\alpha} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\frac{\boldsymbol{\xi}}{\alpha} ; \frac{\boldsymbol{\eta}}{\alpha}\right)
$$

which satisfies

$$
\Delta \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta})=\frac{1}{\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|}, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}, \quad \frac{\partial \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta})}{\partial \boldsymbol{n}}=\delta(\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\eta}), \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}, \quad \int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta}) d \boldsymbol{\xi}=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\eta} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}
$$

and behaves near the singular diagonal $\boldsymbol{\xi}=\boldsymbol{\eta}$ as

$$
\mathcal{G}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta}) \approx \frac{1}{2 \pi\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\eta}\|}-\frac{\mathcal{H}(\boldsymbol{\eta})}{4 \pi} \log (\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\eta}\|)+\mathcal{R}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta}), \quad 0<\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\eta}\| \ll \alpha
$$

where $\mathcal{H}(\boldsymbol{\eta})$ and $\mathcal{R}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta})$ are defined as

$$
\mathcal{H}(\boldsymbol{\eta})=\frac{1}{\alpha} \tilde{H}\left(\frac{\boldsymbol{\eta}}{\alpha}\right), \quad \mathcal{R}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta})=\frac{1}{\alpha} \tilde{R}_{s}\left(\frac{\boldsymbol{\xi}}{\alpha} ; \frac{\boldsymbol{\eta}}{\alpha}\right)+\frac{1}{4 \pi \alpha} \tilde{H}\left(\frac{\boldsymbol{\eta}}{\alpha}\right) \log (\alpha)
$$

with $\mathcal{R}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta})$ that can be approximated as

$$
\mathcal{R}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\eta}) \approx \mathcal{R}_{s}(\boldsymbol{\eta} ; \boldsymbol{\eta})+O\left(\frac{\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\eta}\|}{\alpha}\right)
$$

# A. 2 Weber solution from electrostatics 

Here we provide a justification for why the exit flux can be approximated by the classical Weber solution [32]. We consider

$$
\Delta \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})-\mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}
$$

along with absorbing boundary $\mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})=0$ for $\boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}$. Following [35] we can use the small radius $a_{2} \alpha$ to introduce a set of local cartesian coordinates $\left(\eta, s_{1}, s_{2}\right)$ with which we can map the neighborhood near $\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}$ to the infinite half-space in 3-D. This mapping relies on the expansion of the Laplacian as

$$
\Delta_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}=\frac{1}{\left(\alpha a_{2}\right)^{2}} \Delta_{\left(\eta, s_{1}, s_{2}\right)}+O\left(\frac{1}{\alpha a_{2}}\right)=\frac{1}{\left(\alpha a_{2}\right)^{2}}\left(\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial \eta^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial s_{1}^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial s_{2}^{2}}\right)+O\left(\frac{1}{\alpha a_{2}}\right)
$$

where $\Delta_{\left(\eta, s_{1}, s_{2}\right)}$ is the Laplacian expressed in Cartesian coordinates. By redefining $\mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})$ as $P\left(\eta, s_{1}, s_{2}\right)$ Eq. (A.9) gets transformed as

$$
\left(\frac{1}{\left(\alpha a_{2}\right)^{2}} \Delta_{\left(\eta, s_{1}, s_{2}\right)}+O\left(\frac{1}{\alpha a_{2}}\right)\right) P\left(\eta, s_{1}, s_{2}\right)-P\left(\eta, s_{1}, s_{2}\right)=0
$$

and thus at leading-order we obtain

$$
\Delta_{\left(\eta, s_{1}, s_{2}\right)} P\left(\eta, s_{1}, s_{2}\right)=0,\left.\quad P\right|_{\eta=0}=0, \quad \sqrt{s_{1}^{2}+s_{2}^{2}}<1,\left.\quad \frac{\partial P}{\partial \eta}\right|_{\eta=0}=0, \quad \sqrt{s_{1}^{2}+s_{2}^{2}}>1
$$

$P\left(\eta, s_{1}, s_{2}\right) \rightarrow P_{0}$ as far-field condition $\sqrt{\eta^{2}+s_{1}^{2}+s_{2}^{2}} \rightarrow \infty$. The solution to Eq. (A.12) is given by

$$
P\left(\eta, s_{1}, s_{2}\right)=P_{0}\left(1-\frac{2}{\pi} \int_{0}^{\infty} e^{-\eta m} J_{0}\left(m \sqrt{s_{1}^{2}+s_{2}^{2}}\right) \sin (m) \frac{d m}{m}\right)
$$

where $J_{0}$ is the usual regular Bessel function of order 0 . By then computing the flux we get

$$
\left.\frac{\partial P}{\partial \eta}\right|_{\eta=0}=\frac{2 P_{0}}{\pi} \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-\left(s_{1}^{2}+s_{2}^{2}\right)}}, \quad \sqrt{s_{1}^{2}+s_{2}^{2}}<1
$$

and then when transformed back to the coordinates $\boldsymbol{\xi}$ this becomes

$$
\frac{\partial \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})}{\partial \boldsymbol{\xi}} \sim \frac{1}{\sqrt{\left(\alpha a_{2}\right)^{2}-\left\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right\|^{2}}}, \quad \boldsymbol{\xi} \in \partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}
$$

We can treat similarly the equations for $\mathcal{S}_{i j}$ and $\mathcal{V}$.

# A. 3 Computing boundary flux integrals 

We now derive approximation for the singular integrals from Section $\S 4$ which involve the Neumann Green's function. We first calculate the boundary integrals

$$
\int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi} \quad \text { and } \quad \int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}} \frac{\mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{\sqrt{\alpha a_{2}^{2}-\left\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right\|^{2}}} d \boldsymbol{\xi}
$$

by defining $\rho=\left\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\xi}_{i}\right\|$ and using polar coordinates. We obtain that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi} & =2 \pi \int_{0}^{a_{1} \alpha}\left(\frac{1}{2 \pi \rho}-\frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4 \pi} \log (\rho)+\mathcal{R}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)+O\left(\frac{\rho}{\alpha}\right)\right) \rho d \rho \\
& =\alpha a_{1}-\frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{2} \alpha^{2} a_{1}^{2}\left(\frac{1}{2} \log \left(\alpha a_{1}\right)-\frac{1}{4}\right)+\pi \alpha^{2} a_{1}^{2} \mathcal{R}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)+O\left(\alpha a_{1}^{3}\right) \\
& =\alpha a_{1} f\left(a_{1}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

with $f\left(a_{1}\right)$ defined as

$$
f\left(a_{1}\right)=1-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4} a_{1} \log \left(a_{1}\right)+\alpha a_{1}\left(\pi \mathcal{R}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)+\frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4}\left(\frac{1}{2}-\log (\alpha)\right)\right)+O\left(a_{1}^{2}\right)
$$

but then on the domain $\tilde{\Omega}$ with $O(1)$ length-scale this yields,

$$
f\left(a_{1}\right)=1-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{4} a_{1} \log \left(a_{1}\right)+a_{1}\left(\pi \tilde{R}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)+\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{8}\right)+O\left(a_{1}^{2}\right)
$$

We then proceed similarly with the integral involving the classical Weber solution, and evaluate

$$
\begin{aligned}
\int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}} \frac{\mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{\sqrt{\alpha a_{2}^{2}-\left\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right\|^{2}}} d \boldsymbol{\xi} & =2 \pi \int_{0}^{\alpha a_{2}}\left(\frac{1}{2 \pi \rho}-\frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{4 \pi} \log (\rho)+\mathcal{R}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)+O\left(\frac{\rho}{\alpha}\right)\right) \frac{\rho d \rho}{\sqrt{\left(\alpha a_{2}\right)^{2}-\rho^{2}}} \\
& =\frac{\pi}{2}-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{2} a_{2}\left(\log \left(\alpha a_{2}\right)+\log (2)-1\right)+2 \pi a_{2} \alpha \mathcal{R}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)+O\left(a_{2}^{2}\right) \\
& =\frac{\pi}{2} g\left(a_{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $g\left(a_{2}\right)$ is defined as

$$
g\left(a_{2}\right)=1-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{\pi} a_{2} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+\alpha a_{2}\left(4 \mathcal{R}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)+\frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)}{\pi}(1-\log (2)-\log (\alpha))\right)+O\left(a_{2}^{2}\right)
$$

but then on the domain $\tilde{\Omega}$ with $O(1)$ length-scale this yields

$$
g\left(a_{2}\right)=1-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{\pi} a_{2} \log \left(a_{2}\right)+a_{2}\left(4 \tilde{R}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)+\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{\pi}(1-\log (2))\right)+O\left(a_{2}^{2}\right)
$$

By then assuming that the narrow windows are well-spaced we get the approximation below for the mixed integral terms

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi} \approx \pi\left(a_{1} \alpha\right)^{2} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) \\
& \int_{\partial \Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}}} \frac{\mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{\sqrt{\alpha a_{2}^{2}-\left\|\boldsymbol{\xi}-\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right\|^{2}}} d \boldsymbol{\xi} \approx 2 \pi a_{2} \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

To calculate the last integral in Eq. (4.12c)-(4.12d) we proceed by splitting the domain into three subregions,

$$
\int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}\right) \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi}=\left(\int_{B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \alpha a_{1}\right)}+\int_{B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}, \alpha a_{2}\right)}+\int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}} \backslash\left\{B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \alpha a_{1}\right) \cup B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}, \alpha a_{2}\right)\right\}}\right) \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}\right) \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi}, \quad j=1,2
$$

where $B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}, \alpha a_{j}\right)$ for $j=1,2$ are half-spheres of radius $\alpha a_{j}$ centered in $\boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}$. Outside of these subregions the sum $\mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi})$ is constant, yielding

$$
\int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}} \backslash\left\{B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \alpha a_{1}\right) \cup B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}, \alpha a_{2}\right)\right\}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}\right) \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi} \approx \overline{\mathcal{P}} \int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}} \backslash\left\{B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \alpha a_{1}\right) \cup B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}, \alpha a_{2}\right)\right\}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi} \approx \mathcal{P}[O(1)]
$$

with its contribution that can be neglected, while for the two subregions we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
\int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}\right) \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi} & \approx\left(\int_{B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \alpha a_{1}\right)}+\int_{B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}, \alpha a_{2}\right)}\right) \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}\right) \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi} \\
& \approx \mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \int_{B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \alpha a_{1}\right)} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi}+\mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) \int_{B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}, \alpha a_{2}\right)} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi} \\
& \approx \mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \int_{B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \alpha a_{1}\right)} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi}
\end{aligned}
$$

due to the absorbing boundary condition $\mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)=0$. Here the windows are well-spaced, thus we calculate

$$
\int_{B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \alpha a_{1}\right)} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi} \approx \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)\left|B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \alpha a_{1}\right)\right|=\mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} \alpha^{3} a_{1}^{3}
$$

while around the singularity we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
\int_{B\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}, \alpha a_{1}\right)} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) d \boldsymbol{\xi} & =\int_{\frac{\pi}{2}}^{\pi} \int_{0}^{2 \pi} \int_{0}^{\alpha a_{1}}\left(\frac{1}{2 \pi \rho}-\frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{4 \pi} \log (\rho)+\mathcal{R}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)+O\left(\frac{\rho}{\alpha}\right)\right) \rho^{2} \sin (\theta) d \rho d \phi d \theta \\
& =\frac{\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2}}{2}-\frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{2} \alpha^{3} a_{1}^{3}\left(\frac{1}{3} \log \left(\alpha a_{1}\right)-\frac{1}{9}\right)+2 \pi \mathcal{R}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \frac{\alpha^{3} a_{1}^{3}}{3}+O\left(\alpha a_{1}^{4}\right) \\
& =\frac{\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2}}{2} m\left(a_{1}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $m\left(a_{1}\right)$ is an expansion given by

$$
m\left(a_{1}\right)=1-\alpha \frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{3} a_{1} \log \left(a_{1}\right)+\alpha a_{1}\left(\frac{4 \pi}{3} \mathcal{R}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)+\frac{\mathcal{H}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)}{3}\left(\frac{1}{3}-\log (\alpha)\right)\right)+O\left(a_{1}^{2}\right)
$$

On the domain $\widehat{\Omega}$ with $O(1)$ length-scale this yields

$$
m\left(a_{1}\right)=1-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{3} a_{1} \log \left(a_{1}\right)+a_{1}\left(\frac{4 \pi}{3} \tilde{R}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)+\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{9}\right)+O\left(a_{1}^{2}\right)
$$

and our final approximate integral solutions are

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi} \approx \mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \frac{\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2}}{2} m\left(a_{1}\right) \\
& \int_{\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right) \mathcal{P}(\boldsymbol{\xi}) d \boldsymbol{\xi} \approx \mathcal{P}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \alpha^{3} \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

# B Reduced ionic and voltage asymptotic formulas
## B. 1 Small interior charge

When $\alpha \sim O(1)$, we can expand the ratio $\mathcal{A}$ assuming $a_{1}, a_{2} \ll 1$ as

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{A} & \approx \frac{\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right)\left(1+\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 \alpha a_{2}}\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|\right)+\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \alpha \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right)\left(1+\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right| \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{2} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{1}\right)\right)}{\left(1+\frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} m\left(a_{1}\right)\right)\left(1+\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 \alpha a_{2}}\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|\right)} \\

$$
\begin{aligned}

# B. 2 Large interior charge 

Alternatively if $\alpha \gg 1$, we first remark that

$$
\left|\Omega_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}\right|=\alpha^{3}|\tilde{\Omega}|, \quad \mathcal{G}_{s}\left(\boldsymbol{\xi}_{1} ; \boldsymbol{\xi}_{2}\right)=\alpha \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)
$$

and thus we obtain that

$$
\mathcal{A}=\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}} \frac{\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)\left(\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}+\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}|\tilde{\Omega}|\right)+\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)\left(\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}+|\tilde{\Omega}| \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)}{\left(\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}+\frac{a_{1}^{2}}{2} m\left(a_{1}\right)\right)\left(\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}+\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}|\tilde{\Omega}|\right)-\left(\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}+|\tilde{\Omega}| \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}
$$

$$
\mathcal{A} \approx \frac{1}{\alpha^{2}} \frac{\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}+\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{\frac{a_{1}^{2}}{8 a_{2}} m\left(a_{1}\right) g\left(a_{2}\right)-\tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}

after which we can expand assuming $a_{1} \ll 1$ and $a_{2} \ll 1$, leading to

$$

$$

and then if $a_{1}^{3} \gg \frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}$ we can neglect the ratio $\mathcal{A}$. We proceed similarly for $\mathcal{B}$,

$$
\mathcal{B}=\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}} \frac{\left(\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}+\frac{a_{1}^{2}}{2} m\left(a_{1}\right)\right)\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)+\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{\left(\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}+\frac{a_{1}^{2}}{2} m\left(a_{1}\right)\right)\left(\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}+\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}|\tilde{\Omega}|\right)-\left(\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}+|\tilde{\Omega}| \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}
$$

and then expanding in $\alpha \gg 1$ yields

$$
\mathcal{B} \approx \frac{1}{\alpha^{2}} \frac{\left(\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}}+\frac{a_{1}^{2}}{2} m\left(a_{1}\right)\right)\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)+\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{\frac{a_{1}^{2}}{8 a_{2}} m\left(a_{1}\right) g\left(a_{2}\right)-\tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}

and after some simplifications and keeping only leading-order terms in $a_{1} \ll 1$ and $a_{2} \ll 1$, we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{B} & \approx \frac{\pi}{\alpha^{2}}|\tilde{\Omega}| \frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)-4 a_{2} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)+\frac{16 a_{2}}{3 m\left(a_{1}\right)}\left(f\left(a_{1}\right)-\pi a_{1} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{g\left(a_{2}\right)-\frac{16 \pi a_{1} a_{2}}{3 m\left(a_{1}\right)}\left(\tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)^{2}} \\

$$

on which we can take the limit $\alpha \gg 1$, leading to

$$
\left(m\left(a_{1}\right)-\frac{4 \pi}{3} a_{1} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)\left(\frac{\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}+\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{m\left(a_{1}\right) \frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{4 \pi}{3} a_{1}\left(\tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)^{2}}\right)

which is equivalent to

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(m\left(a_{1}\right)-\frac{4 \pi}{3} a_{1} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)\left(\frac{\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}\right) \frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi\left(\tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)^{2}}{m\left(a_{1}\right) \frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{4 \pi}{3} a_{1}\left(\tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)^{2}}\right) \approx \\

\end{aligned}
$$

and then neglecting terms of $O(1)$ and beyond in terms of the narrow radii $a_{1}$ and $a_{2}$ we get,

$$
\left(m\left(a_{1}\right)-\frac{4 \pi}{3} a_{1} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{1}{2}\left(\alpha a_{1}\right)^{2} \mathcal{A} \approx \frac{1}{a_{1}}-\frac{\tilde{H}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)}{4} \log \left(a_{1}\right)+O(1)

Similarly for the contribution from

$$

we get after taking the limit $\alpha \gg 1$,

\left(\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)\left(\frac{\frac{\alpha_{1}^{2}}{2} m\left(a_{1}\right)\left(\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)+\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{\frac{a_{1}^{2}}{2} m\left(a_{1}\right) \frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\frac{2 \pi}{3} a_{1}^{3}\left(\tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)^{2}}\right)

and then further simplifications yield

$$
\left(g\left(a_{2}\right)-4 a_{2} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)\left(\frac{\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)+\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{4 \pi a_{1}}{3 m\left(a_{1}\right)} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{g\left(a_{2}\right)-\frac{16 \pi a_{1} a_{2}}{3 m\left(a_{1}\right)}\left(\tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)^{2}}\right)

and upon neglecting terms of order $O(1)$ and beyond we get

Similarly for the average voltage with formula given by Eq. (4.35b), we first calculate

$$

$$

and then further simplifications yield

$$
\frac{g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}} \alpha^{2}|\tilde{\Omega}| \mathcal{B} \approx \frac{\frac{\pi g\left(a_{2}\right)}{4 a_{2}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)+\left(\frac{f\left(a_{1}\right)}{a_{1}}-\pi \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right) \frac{4 \pi a_{1}}{3 m\left(a_{1}\right)} \tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2}\right)}{1+\frac{16 \pi a_{1} a_{2}}{3 m\left(a_{1}\right) g\left(a_{2}\right)}\left(\tilde{G}_{s}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{2} ; \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{1}\right)\right)^{2}}

and then neglecting terms of order $O(1)$ and beyond, we are left with

$$

Similarly for the term

$$
\begin{aligned}

abstract:
Characterizing the local voltage distribution within nanophysiological
domains, driven by ionic currents through membrane channels, is crucial for
studying cellular activity in modern biophysics, yet it presents significant
experimental and theoretical challenges. Theoretically, the complexity arises
from the difficulty of solving electro-diffusion equations in three-dimensional
domains. Currently, there are no methods available for obtaining asymptotic
computations or approximated solutions of nonlinear equations, and numerically,
it is challenging to explore solutions across both small and large spatial
scales. In this work, we develop a method to solve the Poisson-Nernst-Planck
equations with ionic currents entering and exiting through two narrow, circular
window channels located on the boundary. The inflow through the first window is
composed of a single cation, while the outflow maintains a constant ionic
density satisfying local electro-neutrality conditions. Employing regular
expansions and Green's function representations, we derive the ionic profiles
and voltage drops in both small and large charge regimes. We explore how local
surface curvature and window channels size influence voltage dynamics and
validate our theoretical predictions through numerical simulations, assessing
the accuracy of our asymptotic computations. These novel relationships between
current, voltage, concentrations and geometry can enhance the characterization
of physiological behaviors of nanodomains.
